    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "> I guess converting all `internal` functions to `public payable` should be fine, but I think `private` functions could be tricky since there could be multiple private functions with the same signature due to contract inheritance, and you can't override them since you shouldn't change their logic in parent contracts...\r\n\r\nThat's a fair point. I'm aware the implementation for this would be hacky.\r\nMaybe instead of converting the functions, a preprocessor could copy them into new `public payable` functions prefixed with the contract name and function visibility. For example:\r\n\r\n```solidity\r\npragma solidity ^0.8.0;\r\ncontract Contract {\r\n    uint256 public value;\r\n    constructor() {\r\n        value = squareOf(2);\r\n    }\r\n    function squareOf(uint256 input) private returns (uint256) {\r\n        return input**2;\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nbecomes:\r\n\r\n```solidity\r\npragma solidity ^0.8.0;\r\ncontract Contract {\r\n    uint256 public value;\r\n    constructor() {\r\n        value = squareOf(2);\r\n    }\r\n    function squareOf(uint256 input) private returns (uint256) {\r\n        return input**2;\r\n    }\r\n    function Contract__private__squareOf(uint256 input) public payable returns (uint256) {\r\n        return input**2;\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n",
